    "created_at": "2024-06-03T14:34:44Z",
    "updated_at": "2024-06-03T14:34:44Z",
    "body": "Can confirm, I'm seeing the same thing in iTerm2 (Build 3.5.0) with the `❄️` emoji. I used a hex editor to figure out how it encodes as utf-8, and the sequence is:\r\n\r\n```\r\n00000000: e29d 84ef b88f                           ......\r\n```\r\n\r\nYou'll notice the initial 3 bytes are the [\"snowflake\" emoji unicode code point,](https://www.compart.com/en/unicode/U+2744) followed by `ef b8 8f`, which is the [`variant selector-16` (codepoint 0xFE0F)](https://www.compart.com/en/unicode/U+FE0F).\r\n\r\nI expect that if either `fill` isn't set up to deal with \"hidden\" characters like those variant selectors, in exactly the same way that the terminal expects them (one thinking it's 1 character wide and the other thinking it's 2), that would cause annoying issues with right-justified prompts.",
